09:56.860 --> 10:03.125
the help of the faculty, with the fact of using our 
resources wisely. And that's what I'm saying was a

10:03.746 --> 10:07.129
management type of thing. procedure that we went 
through. So I'm kind of proud of that, too. That was

10:10.701 --> 10:12.203
one of the other aspects. And I spoke about 
recruitment of minorities. So what do I see for the

10:17.589 --> 10:20.452
21st century? Well, I think I see something not too 
dissimilar from some ideas that I put forward. I

10:28.460 --> 10:34.267
had an article that I was invited to write for my 
specialty is English education. And an

10:34.867 --> 10:37.470
organization I belong to called Conference on 
English Education. And they had two journals that

10:40.898 --> 10:46.665
they devoted to invited articles, and one journal 
was on needed research. And they asked me to write

10:47.446 --> 10:50.610
an article in that regard. And one of the things I 
said was that I believed that in the very near

10:51.811 --> 11:03.205
future, one of the things that we would be doing in 
teacher education is to try to prepare teacher

11:04.653 --> 11:07.576
scholars who are also researchers. In other 
words, teacher researchers. And I believe that we

11:10.519 --> 11:17.526
are just on the horizon of doing that at Susannan 
University. And it's right in keeping with the

11:17.546 --> 11:29.998
Holmes Group agenda in terms of major research 
institutions becoming involved in teacher

11:17.546 --> 11:29.998
education. That's why I'm so proud of that. I'll 
take a copy of that article. And I think what's

11:34.589 --> 11:53.193
going to happen is that we're going to have much 
more collaboration of our faculty with public

11:34.589 --> 11:53.193
school teachers in the area of classroom research 
so that it's out there where it's taking place. And

11:54.094 --> 12:01.423
I think that we're going to find that our whole 
thrust will be in producing these teacher

12:01.977 --> 12:10.767
scholars who are also researchers, and that our 
faculty are going to build that research base that

12:01.977 --> 12:10.767
our teachers may not have. But the two of them 
together, with the practical experience of a

12:11.088 --> 12:18.496
teacher coupled with the research expertise of 
our faculty, could do wonders. Just do wonders. I

12:19.818 --> 12:21.219
think I see that on our horizon. So you're not 
apprehensive about this new program that is about

12:21.259 --> 12:26.546
to come about? You think that it has a positive? I 
mean, everybody's sold. I think we have an

12:29.469 --> 12:31.191
opportunity. I think I'm optimistic about it. And 
are you able to project that to your faculty? I

12:41.583 --> 12:42.825
think to some degree. I would be less than honest if 
I didn't tell you that there are some faculty that

12:43.025 --> 12:50.156
are reticent about what's happening. They're not 
certain that we have proven that one thing is

12:50.217 --> 12:56.166
better than another. My feeling is we could go on 
for years and never have proof. We have to move

13:00.425 --> 13:01.628
forward. I think the climate now, the educational 
reform is saying, as parents were saying, we

13:03.091 --> 13:14.155
expect our teachers to be fully prepared and to be 
scholars. and to be able to not only make a

13:14.523 --> 13:21.070
diagnosis, but be able to make a remediation if 
that's necessary. And you can't do that unless you

13:21.170 --> 13:23.132
have a scholar researcher. Do you think, though, 
that it's going to affect teacher shortage? I

13:26.215 --> 13:30.119
mean, we already have a teacher shortage, but is 
that going to make it worse? In other words,

13:30.199 --> 13:40.210
prevent people from going into teaching because 
they feel like it's, you know, five years and then

13:30.199 --> 13:40.210
you come out and you're not making as much as... 
That's what I'm hearing from a lot of people. How do

13:43.868 --> 13:45.089
you respond to that? Because I'm having trouble 
responding.

13:49.993 --> 13:55.078
I'm going to say this, and I hope it's taken the 
right way.

13:59.141 --> 14:04.166
I mentioned earlier about my career being spent in 
major research institutions. And I believe Texas

14:05.207 --> 14:09.150
A&M University is such an institution.

14:11.645 --> 14:15.711
And I believe teacher education is part of that 
research agenda.

14:18.735 --> 14:28.550
And our role is to produce the educational leaders 
of tomorrow.

14:32.135 --> 14:40.167
If it has some effect on the numbers that we are able 
to produce, then I say that must be balanced by the

14:41.817 --> 15:02.285
even higher quality of individual we will be 
putting out who will go out there and work with

14:41.817 --> 15:02.285
those people who didn't graduate from Texas A&M 
University and will lead in education and will be

14:41.817 --> 15:02.285
on the cutting edge of what happens. Now, just 
think about what that would mean to this

15:02.325 --> 15:07.412
institution and to education if that were to 
occur. Then we become the seed institution for

15:10.454 --> 15:15.942
educational reform for how many years to come? And 
that's why I'm optimistic. And I think that would

15:17.784 --> 15:30.722
be exciting for a faculty to begin to work with the 
high quality students that we have coming to us and

15:17.784 --> 15:30.722
follow them through into a professional career. 
That's my view. That's a very bright outlook. And I

15:34.307 --> 15:36.410
think that should be appreciated. And I hope that 
everybody would feel that way, because it is. so

15:40.087 --> 15:40.808
important. And I really appreciate your time and 
all of this very good insights because it's a

15:41.289 --> 15:47.501
totally different. No, I really appreciate it. 
And I hope that you let me come back and ask a few

15:49.645 --> 15:55.557
questions as I start to synthesize all of it. I know 
I'll have to.

